{"success": true, "context": "Blake Snyder in 'Save the Cat' (p.75-80) describes the midpoint as either a 'false victory' or a 'false defeat' — where everything seems to go right (or wrong) before the real complications begin. The midpoint raises the stakes permanently and cross the story from fun and games into the serious second half.

Robert McKee in 'Story' (p.240-248) calls this the 'Major Reversal of Act Two' — the point where the protagonist's understanding of reality fundamentally shifts. What they believed was true is revealed as false. This creates the progressive complications that drive the second half.

John Truby in 'Anatomy of Story' (p.210-215) calls this 'the revelation' — a crucial piece of information that reframes everything. The best revelations are ones that change the audience's understanding as well as the protagonist's.", "citations": [{"document_title": "Save the Cat by Blake Snyder", "page_range": "75-80", "chapter": "The Board", "quote": "The midpoint raises the stakes permanently.", "formatted": "[Save the Cat, p.75-80]"}, {"document_title": "Story by Robert McKee", "page_range": "240-248", "chapter": "Part 3", "quote": "What they believed was true is revealed as false.", "formatted": "[Story, p.240-248]"}, {"document_title": "The Anatomy of Story by John Truby", "page_range": "210-215", "chapter": "Story Structure", "quote": "The best revelations change the audience's understanding as well as the protagonist's.", "formatted": "[Anatomy of Story, p.210-215]"}]}
